That's expected — as I explained, `course.currency` is `"USD"` (not blank), so it hits the second `if` and returns `"USD"` before ever reaching the offerings.

You need to **swap the priority** — check offerings first, course currency last. Update your code to this:

```java
//public String getCurrency() { return course != null ? nvl(course.currency) : ""; }
public String getCurrency() {
    if (course == null) return "";
    if (course.offeringsList != null && !course.offeringsList.isEmpty()
            && StringUtils.isNotBlank(course.offeringsList.get(0).currency)) {
        return nvl(course.offeringsList.get(0).currency);
    }
    return nvl(course.currency);
}
```

The key change: offerings are checked **before** `course.currency`, so the country-specific currency (e.g. `MYR`) is returned instead of the hardcoded `USD` from the course level.

That confirms the root cause. The API returns **"USD"** at **both** the course level and offering level — the API doesn't provide country-specific currency for this course. So the Java fallback to offerings won't help either.

Since the API doesn't give us the right currency, the only option is the **hardcoded country → currency map** I mentioned earlier. We map `useLocation` (e.g. `"Malaysia"`) to the correct currency code (`"MYR"`).

Here's the updated `getCurrency()`:

```java
public String getCurrency() {
    if (course == null) return "";
    Map<String, String> currencyMap = new HashMap<>();
    currencyMap.put("United States", "USD");
    currencyMap.put("Malaysia", "MYR");
    currencyMap.put("United Kingdom", "GBP");
    currencyMap.put("Australia", "AUD");
    currencyMap.put("Canada", "CAD");
    currencyMap.put("Singapore", "SGD");
    currencyMap.put("India", "INR");
    // add more as needed...

    String mapped = currencyMap.get(useLocation);
    if (mapped != null) return mapped;
    return nvl(course.currency); // fallback to API value
}
```

But before I apply this — **do you know the full list of countries your site supports?** That way we can add them all at once rather than adding them one by one later.

This confirms the pattern clearly:

| Course | Price | API Currency |
|--------|-------|-------------|
| Free (On Demand) | 0.0 | **USD** (always, wrong) |
| Paid (On Demand) | 5820 | **MYR** (correct) |

So the API only returns the correct currency when price > 0. For free courses it always defaults to USD.

The Java fix needs to: **use `useLocation` to determine currency only when price is 0**, since paid courses already work correctly.

```java
public String getCurrency() {
    if (course == null) return "";
    if (course.price != 0) return nvl(course.currency); // paid: API is correct
    return getCurrencyByLocation(useLocation);           // free: derive from location
}

private String getCurrencyByLocation(String location) {
    if (StringUtils.isBlank(location)) return "USD";
    switch (location) {
        case "Malaysia":       return "MYR";
        case "United Kingdom": return "GBP";
        case "Australia":      return "AUD";
        case "Canada":         return "CAD";
        case "Singapore":      return "SGD";
        case "India":          return "INR";
        default:               return "USD";
    }
}
```

Before I apply this — **what countries does your site support?** I need the full list so the `switch` is complete from day one. Otherwise we'll keep adding them one by one later.

